{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17617697","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17617697"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T15:15:34+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T15:15:34+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16485"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16485","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16485"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.23,0.13,0.53,0.05,0.05]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9176"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"68701"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9176","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9176"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16485"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"54158"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4926"},{"type":"tags","id":"4927"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"},{"type":"tags","id":"5028"},{"type":"tags","id":"5086"},{"type":"tags","id":"10104"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21783"},{"type":"contributions","id":"22631"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"68701","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/68701"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EPulmonary arterial hypertension is characterised by elevated pressure in the pulmonary circulation. Several drug classes are used to treat this condition by promoting vasodilation of pulmonary vessels.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the mechanism of action of phosphodiesterase type 5 inhibitors (such as sildenafil and tadalafil) in treating pulmonary hypertension?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Blocks calcium channels in vascular smooth muscle","Antagonises endothelin receptors","Increases cyclic guanosine monophosphate levels","Stimulates beta-2 adrenergic receptors","Increases prostacyclin levels"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPhosphodiesterase type 5 inhibitors increase cyclic guanosine monophosphate levels\u003C/strong\u003E by preventing its breakdown. This leads to smooth muscle relaxation in pulmonary vessels and reduces pulmonary vascular resistance. Examples include sildenafil and tadalafil.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBlocks calcium channels in vascular smooth muscle\u003C/strong\u003E describes is the mechanism of calcium channel blockers like nifedipine. \u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAntagonism of endothelin receptors\u003C/strong\u003E describes the mechanism of endothelin receptor antagonists like bosentan. \u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EStimulates beta-2 adrenergic receptors\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect; while beta-2 agonists can cause some vasodilation, this is not their primary use in pulmonary hypertension. \u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAn \u003Cstrong\u003Eincrease in prostacyclin levels\u003C/strong\u003E is seen in prostacyclin analogues like epoprostenol. \u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe increased cyclic guanosine monophosphate leads to decreased intracellular calcium, resulting in vasodilation of pulmonary vessels and improved symptoms of pulmonary hypertension.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Phosphodiesterase type 5 inhibitors increase cyclic guanosine monophosphate levels, leading to smooth muscle relaxation in pulmonary vessels.","Endothelin receptor antagonists block the vasoconstricting effects of endothelin-1 in pulmonary vessels.","Prostacyclin analogues activate adenylate cyclase to increase cyclic adenosine monophosphate, causing vasodilation."],"references":["Therapeutic Guidelines. Melbourne: Therapeutic Guidelines Limited. Available from: https://www.tg.org.au","Ritter J, Flower RJ (Rod J), Henderson G (Graeme), et al.\u00a0Rang and Dale\u2019s Pharmacology. Tenth edition. Elsevier; 2024.","Australian Medicines Handbook\u00a0(online). Adelaide: Australian Medicines Handbook Pty Ltd. Available from:\u00a0https://amhonline.amh.net.au/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"54158"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16485"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"54158","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/54158"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-10T11:30:57+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-10T11:31:38+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9176"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"68701"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"descrip